<DOC><DOCNO> AP880802-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2312EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Flood     08-02 0289</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Flood,0297</SECOND><HEAD>Rescuers Search for More Than 400 Missing in Flood Disaster</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Floods caused by sudden heavy rains left 225people dead and 449 missing and affected nearly 100,000 residentsof coastal Zhejiang province, China's official Xinhua News Agencyreported Tuesday.   Downpours from Friday evening through Saturday poured up to 19.6inches of rain in 12 hours on parts of five hard-hit countiesaround Ningbo, a prosperous commercial city on the East China Sea.   Xinhua said water resources in flood-hit areas were polluted anddrinking water supplies were inadequate.   An official of the Zhejiang provincial Foreign Affairs Office,identifying himself only as Huang, said helicopters rescued somepeople stranded by floods. He said floodwaters had covered 154,400acres of farmland. About half the waters now have receded, he said.   The official China Daily newspaper quoted an unidentifiedofficial of the provincial Flooding and Drought CombatingDepartment as saying Tuesday that those missing were ``not likelyto survive.''   He said it was the worst flooding disaster to hit Zhejiang in 40years, destroying 16,949 homes, 100 reservoirs and 305 bridges. Heput the economic loss at $167 million.   It was the second storm this summer to pound Zhejiang, one ofChina's richest provinces. Torrential rains in late June killed 45.   At least 750 people have been reported killed in floods ravagingcoastal, southern and northern China this year, while wide areas ofcentral China are suffering from one of the worst droughts inmemory.   Searing temperatures in Shanghai, Nanjing and other cities alongthe Yangtze River have been linked to more than 500 deaths.   Rain-swollen rivers led to two boat accidents in Sichuanprovince late last month which left 103 dead and at least 100missing.</TEXT></DOC>